body:
Some math ops have very bad numerical stability and essential randomness (e.g., exp/log with reduction on large elements). To maintain the same test coverage with lower CI failing rate, we can gradually replace flaky tests' RTG with the ones implemented in this PR --- try Discrete first. If still unstable, use Circular.

Overall recommended strategy to handle flaky test
- Find if it uses `Uniform` in `onnxruntime/test/common/tensor_op_test_utils.h`. If yes, replace `Uniform` with `Discrete` implemented in this PR. For `candidate_values`, we can try `[-2, -1.5, -1, -0.5, 0, 0.5, 1, 1.5, 2]`, `[-2, -1, 0, 1, 2]`, `[-1, 0, 1]`, and `[0, 1]` and choose the most difficult one among those passing 100 runs.
- If `Discrete` fails to meet the stability requirement, switch to `Circular` and repeat the `candidate_values` selection process.

Let's keep an eye on the two bugs mentioned in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/15515. If the related unit tests fail again, we can replace the underlying `RandomValueGenerator::Uniform` with `FixedPatternValueGenerator::Descrete` or `FixedPatternValueGenerator::Circular` implemented in this PR.

title: Fix logic error with TensorRT engine cache decryption
body:
The current implementation has logic errors when TRT engine cache and engine cache encryption are both enabled. This commit fixes that issue.

### Description
Change the logic for reading, decryption and deserialization of the Tensor RT engine cache.


### Motivation and Context
This pull request fixes errors in the TensorRT EP when engine cache and engine encryption are both enabled. This problem was reported in issue #12551 but it looks like the issue was not well described/understood. 

Pseudocode of existing implementation:
```
if( engine_cache_enable && engine_file )
   engine_buffer = read(engine_file)
   deserialize(engine_buffer)  <-- If engine_decryption_enable==true, this fails because the content was not decrypted
else if (engine_decryption_enable && engine_cache_enable_ && !engine_file)
   engine_buffer = decrypt(engine_file)  <-- engine cache file does not exist, so this fails
   deserialize(engine_buffer)
else
   //build the engine
...
```
If the engine_file exists and is encrypted, the existing code enters the first if statement, which is not right.

I propose this pseudocode in this pull request:
```
if( engine_cache_enable && engine_file )
   if( engine_decryption_enable )
      engine_buffer = decrypt(engine_file)
   else
      engine_buffer = read(engine_file)
   deserialize(engine_buffer)
else
   //build the engine
...
```
This has the added benefit that the call to deserialize is in one place only and makes for easier maintenance.

title: Improve marshalling of strings in CreateStringTensor
body:
This should resolve https://github.com/dotnet/machinelearning/issues/6620

The previous logic was correct, but it was creating `tensor.Length` managed arrays and `tensor.Length` GCHandles on top of that to ensure pinning. Disposal of GCHandles can be quite expensive as can having all of these short lived allocations in the form of the arrays as it increases GC pressure.

This new approach changes to using a `MarshaledString` and `MarshaledStringArray` helper. This ends up doing native allocations instead which means they are implicitly pinned, doesn't increase GC pressure, and doesn't require costly GCHandles.

From local testing, @michaelgsharp saw that this was between 2-5x faster.

This isn't necessarily the "best" it could be. Depending on exactly what's being done, it could be more optimal to allocate 1x big native allocation and converting all the strings to it sequentially. We could likewise transcode the data directly to the native memory rather than doing it in managed and then copying.

It looks like `OrtFillStringTensor` is basically just copying all the individual strings into a linearized buffer and so is effectively doing the "1x big native allocation" and so some other considerations may be "even better", but as is this should significantly helper the perf of the scenario in question.

There may be other places that are doing similar things with marshalling that could be switched over.

title: Symbolic shape inference replacing/sharing dim_params incorrectly (as part of transformer optimization)

labels.name: ep:DML
labels.description: issues related to the DirectML execution provider

body:
### Describe the issue

I am converting the PyTorch Stable Diffusion models (runwayml/stable-diffusion-v1-5) to ONNX, and then optimizing the pipeline using [onnxruntime.transformers.optimizer](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/optimizer.py) to optimize the Stable Diffusion models for GPU inference in float16. The conversion to float16 requires [running symbolic shape inference](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/5ebe700a9b7514bb6dfa951df34cffb4548196c0/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/onnx_model.py#L621) just before conversion, and this is where the issue occurs: symbolic shape inference is renaming various symbol names in the graph input/output tensors such that they are no longer distinct.

Before symbolic shape inference:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3835701/232169606-29770b08-c069-4a6f-8b57-0f6b365c8fcf.png)

After symbolic shape inference:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/3835701/232169641-9c5fcd1f-8a59-4401-b39b-7a01820772f6.png)

It might appear like this is not an issue in this example, since batch dimensions are typically all the same size for inputs, but in Stable Diffusion inference it's common to have the `sample` and `encoder_hidden_states` [double the batch size for classifier free guidance](https://github.com/huggingface/diffusers/blob/46c52f9b9607e6ecb29c782c052aea313e6487b7/src/diffusers/pipelines/stable_diffusion/pipeline_stable_diffusion.py#L672). In other words, you might see `sample=[2,4,64,64]`, `timestep=[1]`, and `encoder_hidden_states=[2,77,768]`.

The actual renaming is not deterministic (see repro steps below), and sometimes all three inputs share some names. Having unique symbolic dimension names for the inputs is important, since it is desirable for runtime performance to override these dimensions with fixed values (e.g. using free dimension name overrides).



### To reproduce

Torch 1.13.1 is required to avoid [conversion issue](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/97262).
```
pip install torch==1.13.1 transformers diffusers onnx onnxruntime
```

The following code will download the U-Net model from Stable Diffusion v1.5, convert it, and then show the input/output shapes before and after symbolic shape inference.

```python
import onnx
from pathlib import Path
from onnxruntime.transformers.shape_infer_helper import SymbolicShapeInferenceHelper

def print_tensor(tensor):
    name = tensor.name
    tensor_type = tensor.type.tensor_type
    data_type = onnx.TensorProto.DataType.keys()[tensor_type.elem_type]
    shape = [
        dim.dim_param if dim.dim_param else dim.dim_value
        for dim in tensor_type.shape.dim
    ]
    print(f"{name} = {data_type} {shape}")


def print_io(model):
    for tensor in model.graph.input:
        print_tensor(tensor)
    for tensor in model.graph.output:
        print_tensor(tensor)


def convert_sd_model(model_type, output_onnx_path):
    from diffusers import UNet2DConditionModel
    import torch

    pytorch_model = UNet2DConditionModel.from_pretrained(
        "runwayml/stable-diffusion-v1-5", subfolder=model_type
    )

    inputs = {
        "sample": torch.rand((1, 4, 64, 64), dtype=torch.float32),
        "timestep": torch.rand((1,), dtype=torch.float32),
        "encoder_hidden_states": torch.rand((1, 77, 768), dtype=torch.float32),
        "return_dict": False,
    }

    torch.onnx.export(
        pytorch_model,
        inputs,
        str(output_onnx_path),
        export_params=True,
        opset_version=14,
        input_names=["sample", "timestep", "encoder_hidden_states", "return_dict"],
        output_names=["out_sample"],
        dynamic_axes={
            "sample": {0: "sample_n", 1: "sample_c", 2: "sample_h", 3: "sample_w"},
            "timestep": {0: "timestep_n"},
            "encoder_hidden_states": {0: "hidden_n", 1: "hidden_seq"},
        },
    )


# Convert SD U-Net to ONNX if it already doesn't exist
onnx_file_path = Path("unet.onnx")
if not onnx_file_path.exists():
    convert_sd_model("unet", onnx_file_path)

# Print input/output shapes
print("\n*** BEFORE ***")
onnx_model = onnx.load(onnx_file_path, load_external_data=False)
print_io(onnx_model)

# Run symbolic shape inference
shape_infer_helper = SymbolicShapeInferenceHelper(onnx_model, verbose=0)
onnx_model = shape_infer_helper.infer_shapes(
    onnx_model, auto_merge=True, guess_output_rank=False
)

# Print input/output shapes again
print("\n\n*** AFTER ***")
print_io(onnx_model)
```

Example output:
```
*** BEFORE ***
sample = FLOAT ['sample_n', 'sample_c', 'sample_h', 'sample_w']
timestep = FLOAT ['timestep_n']
encoder_hidden_states = FLOAT ['hidden_n', 'hidden_seq', 768]
out_sample = FLOAT ['Convout_sample_dim_0', 4, 'Convout_sample_dim_2', 'Convout_sample_dim_3']


*** AFTER ***
sample = FLOAT ['sample_n', 'sample_c', 'sample_h', 'sample_w']
timestep = FLOAT ['sample_n']
encoder_hidden_states = FLOAT ['hidden_n', 'hidden_seq', 768]
out_sample = FLOAT ['sample_n', 4, 'sample_h', 'sample_w']
```

Note how `timestep` now shares a batch dimension name with `sample`! Furthermore, the behavior seems nondeterministic. On another run of the same script all inputs somehow have `hidden_n` for batch dimension:

```
*** BEFORE ***
sample = FLOAT ['sample_n', 'sample_c', 'sample_h', 'sample_w']
timestep = FLOAT ['timestep_n']
encoder_hidden_states = FLOAT ['hidden_n', 'hidden_seq', 768]
out_sample = FLOAT ['Convout_sample_dim_0', 4, 'Convout_sample_dim_2', 'Convout_sample_dim_3']


*** AFTER ***
sample = FLOAT ['hidden_n', 'sample_c', 'sample_h', 'sample_w']
timestep = FLOAT ['hidden_n']
encoder_hidden_states = FLOAT ['hidden_n', 'hidden_seq', 768]
out_sample = FLOAT ['hidden_n', 4, 'sample_h', 'sample_w']
```

### Urgency

There is some urgency in this issue. Please e-mail my Microsoft alias (justoeck) for details.

title: Add Bluestein Z-Chirp CPU EP implementation for the DFT operator
body:
Add Bluestein Z-Chirp CPU EP implementation for the DFT operator

While the current DFT operator has an FFT implementation for signal lengths of size 2^N, it currently only has a naive implementation for completeness sake. The non-power of 2 case is very slow.

The appropriate algorithm to use here is the Bluestein Z-Chirp algorithm, which evalutates a single DFT with 3 FFT calculations (2 forwards and 1 inverse) and a chirp signal. Luckily, the chirp signal and one of these FFT operations can be precomputed (B).

The resulting computation performs multiple DFTs on longer signals, but in the end is faster because the individual sub-DFT computations can leverage the faster FFT implementation under the hood.

title: [C# ] Improve string marshalling and reduce GC pressure
body:
### Description

  Reduce a number of auxillary objects created to reduce GC pressure.
     Eliminate GCHandle type of memory pinning in most of the places.
     Improve string marshalling by allocating unmanaged memory that does not
     require pinning.     Change native methods from `IntPtr` to `byte[]` (marshalling pinning is more efficient).
     Allocate input/output UTF-8 names in unmanaged heap for the lifetime of InferenceSession. So we do not keep converting them and pinning on every Run.
     Introduce a new native API that allows to allocate and convert/copy strings directly into a native tensor.

The PR delivers around 50% latency improvements and less GC pauses.

Inspired by: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/15520

### Motivation and Context
Client experience GC pressure and performance degradation when dealing with string tensors.

title: Support explicit TRT profiles from provider options
body:
Previous behavior of TRT EP to set TRT optimization profiles for dynamic shape input is based on input tensor values. Users can't explicitly specify the profiles.

This PR makes users capable of specifying min/max/opt profiles through newly added three provider options:

`trt_profile_min_shapes`, `trt_profile_max_shapes` and `trt_profile_opt_shapes` 
with the format of "input1:dim1xdim2...,input2:dim3xdim4...".
(Note: It's similar to --minShapes, --maxShapes and --optShapes of trtexec command-line [flags](https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/tensorrt/developer-guide/index.html#trtexec-flags))

For example, if you are using onnxruntime_perf_test, you can try this:

`./onnxruntime_perf_test -e tensorrt -r 1 -i "trt_profile_min_shapes|imgs:1x3x384x288 trt_profile_max_shapes|imgs:32x3x384x288 trt_profile_opt_shapes|imgs:16x3x384x288" your_model_path`

If the engine cache is enabled, you still need to provide these three explicit provider options in order to use this feature. ORT TRT will compare the min/max/opt profile shape with the ones saved in .profile file to decide whether to rebuild the engine.

Constraints to use these provider options: (1) Need to specify min/max/opt profile shapes for all the dynamic shape input 

 

This feature is also requested by other users:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/13851

title: Add EP specific Resize handling to the transpose optimizer
body:
### Description
<!-- Describe your changes. -->
Add ability to plug in EP specific handling of the Resize operator. Currently that is done with `#ifdef` statements to hardcode behavior if CUDA/ROCm/QNN are enabled at build time, but that is incorrect as there is no guarantee those EPs will be enabled at runtime and assigned the Resize node.
- add EP aware Resize handler that changes the behavior based on the enabled EPs
  - until the Resize node is assigned to an EP exclude it from transpose optimization
   
As we now need EP assignment to take place to complete the transpose optimization:
- update TransposeLayoutForEP to work for any EP
  - if EP wants NHWC it will insert Transpose nodes around layout sensitive nodes
  - if EP wants NCHW it will leave layout sensitive nodes as-is
  - the transpose optimizer is run at the end to allow EP specific changes
- call TransposeLayoutForEP for each EP during graph partitioning

   
### Motivation and Context

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here. -->

### Describe the issue

This build breaks DirectML on Intel integrated GPU. The build has date: Saturday, January 21, 2023 

I spent ages testing all the different builds and I have found that this build breaks [this model](https://huggingface.co/cerebras/Cerebras-GPT-111M) on Intel integrated GPU. The previous build outputs perfect LLM model text. On this build onwards it outputs garbage in DirectML mode. (But gives correct results when run in CPU mode). I haven't investigated which exact op or layer it breaks. I have also tested it on NVidia Quadro P5000 which works fine as expected.

This appears to be the build that goes from opset 17 to opset 18. So perhaps that has something to do with it. Was there a major change in this build that's messed things up for Intel GPUs?

It is broken from this build right through to the latest build (15). But works on all previous builds.


On previous builds when trying to run a quantized model it outputs the message:
